# Radar Image Fetching

All times are UTC. A new image is published every 5 minutes on marks divisible
by 5 (00:00, 00:05, …). Generation takes a few seconds and a country may publish
several minutes late, so a just-passed mark can 404 — handle errors gracefully.

## Core architecture (do not break)

- A single idempotent `reconcile()` drives the whole pipeline:
  sync observed placeholders → `syncForecastPlaceholders` → one sequential fetch
  pass. It is safe to call repeatedly (dedup + disk cache prevent double
  downloads); this is what keeps the logic small. Don't add parallel fetch paths.
- Two timers feed `reconcile()`: `updateTimer` (fires at the next publish
  boundary) and `retryTimer` (re-runs while any frame still has retry budget).
- One fetch pass at a time via `fetchCancellable`. `NetworkService.fetchFrames`
  is a strict queue (`flatMap(maxPublishers: .max(1))`): one request in flight,
  processed in the order given (callers pass newest-first).
- Frame identity is `RadarFrameID` (kind + 5-min source mark). Match network
  results to placeholders with `frameID` — NEVER by recomputing a URL/cache key.
  `RadarFrameID` is quality-independent so matching survives a quality change.
- `fetchFrames` is the single owner of "deliver each result on the main queue".
  Do not add redundant `receive(on:)` hops in the manager or per-request path.

## Observed images

- Sequential, newest → oldest; the prioritized queue must stay visible (exactly
  one box shows as loading at a time — frames are marked loading lazily via the
  `onStart` callback, not all at once).
- Per-product `publishDelaySeconds` is a soft lower bound: it shifts both the
  target timestamp (`Date.radarTimestamps`) and the update-timer firing
  (`secondsUntilNextRadarUpdate`) so we don't ping before an image can exist.

## Forecast images

- Observed-before-forecast: a generation's forecast is fetched only after its
  observed image has loaded (gate in `framesPendingFetch`: forecast source must
  be ≤ newest loaded observed).
- Always seed the newest generation's forecast placeholders (fixed box count);
  fetching stays gated, so seeding never fetches early.
- Keep the previous forecast on screen until the new one loads its first frame
  (`displayedForecastSource`) — no flicker at the 5-minute handoff.
- Cold-start fallback: if the newest generation's forecast isn't generated yet
  and nothing is on screen, also seed the previous generation (server keeps it)
  instead of showing red boxes; promote to newest once it arrives.
- Failed-newest re-anchor: if the newest observed mark didn't load (404s past its
  publish delay) but an older observed did, immediately seed the forecast for the
  newest LOADED observed so it gets fetched. Do NOT wait for the newest mark to
  burn its retry budget — its own forecast is gated until it loads anyway, so the
  user would otherwise stare at disabled boxes for the whole ~50s retry window
  even though we already hold a real observed image (and the server keeps older
  generations ~24h). If the newest mark later succeeds on retry, follow-newest
  promotes its generation over this one.
- `timelineForecastSource` never picks a generation whose observed never loaded:
  it chooses the loaded generation (`displayedForecastSource`), else the newest
  generation that is both fetchable (source ≤ newest loaded observed) and not
  fully failed, else (true cold start) the newest source present. This is what
  keeps the failed-newest case from flashing the dead generation's boxes.
- Anchored to the newest loaded observed; fetched close → far (+10 … +60 min).

## Selection (RadarImageSequence)

`currentImageIndex` is positional, but `loadedImages` reshuffles as frames load,
so re-anchor on every change via `restoreSelection` (matching by `RadarFrameID`,
NEVER by timestamp — an observed and a forecast can share a wall-clock time).
Net behavior:

- Sitting on a forecast → a new observed arrives → snap to that newest observed.
- Sitting on the newest observed → stays following newest.
- Scrubbed back to an _older_ observed frame → position preserved (not at the
  leading edge, so no jump).
- Background forecast frames loading while on a forecast → no jump (not observed),
  so the user keeps watching their forecast until a real new observation lands.
- During animation the jump is suppressed so it doesn't fight the play cursor.
- Forecast generation handoff: if the exact offset hasn't loaded yet in the new
  generation, keep the nearest forecast offset (`nearestForecastIndex`) instead
  of snapping to newest.

"Leading edge" = newest observed OR any forecast (the future). The observed frame
of a generation publishes before its forecast, so a new 5-min mark lands you on
the new observed first, then its forecast generation loads.

## Retry & errors

- Bounded retries, single cadence (`Constants.Radar.retryInterval`): observed
  ~5 attempts, forecast ~10 (generation can lag). 404/HTTP errors settle a frame
  as `failed` without breaking the rest.
- Self-healing: the reconcile + retry loop runs until everything resolves.
  `handlePassCompletion` fails any frame left stranded in `loading`, so there is
  no "stuck grey box until manual reload".
- Failed-frame revival: `requeueFailedFrames` clears the retry budget of in-window
  failed frames (back to `pending`). Triggered only on explicit "try again"
  moments - the publish boundary (`updateTimer`), manual reload, and foreground -
  NEVER from `reconcile` (that would make the bounded fast-retry a tight loop).
  Without it, a frame that 404'd before it was generated (newest mark on a
  late-publishing product) burns its ~50s budget and is then skipped by both
  `framesPendingFetch` and `promoteRetryableToPending`, so neither a passing
  publish cycle nor the reload button can revive it - only an app relaunch.
- `errorMessage` is only surfaced when nothing is displayable and no fetch/retry
  is still possible.

## Display (RadarImageSequence.timelineFrames)

- Fixed box count: observed (`imageCount`) + one forecast generation's offsets.
  The count must never change dynamically as frames load — that's the point of
  placeholders.
- Show a single coherent forecast generation, never two interleaved.
- Order is structural — observed (oldest → newest) then the forecast tail (by
  offset) — and `timelineFrames` already returns it that way. NEVER re-sort the
  combined list by raw `timestamp` in the view: a retained previous generation
  (5 min stale on a normal handoff, far more right after a long background) has
  absolute forecast times (`source + offset`) that overlap the current observed
  window, so a timestamp sort interleaves forecast boxes among the observed ones.

## Lifecycle

- Foreground: `resumeForForeground` realigns the timer and jumps back to the
  newest frame (refetches); never leave the user on a stale selected frame.
- Background: cancel timers and in-flight downloads (`pauseForBackground`).
- Reload cleanly on product, interval, or image-quality change; never reuse the
  previous product's frames (`removeAllImages`).

## Network & caching

- HTTP/3 priority: newest observed (<5 min) highest, forecast + recent observed
  medium, historical observed (>30 min) lowest.
- Request de-duplication: identical in-flight requests share one download.
- File-system cache: 50 MB limit, 7-day expiration, served instantly on hit;
  undecodable entries are dropped and refetched. Cache the original bytes
  verbatim to preserve the embedded `GeoBox` PNG metadata.
- No URLCache: the session opts out (`config.urlCache = nil`, requests use
  `.reloadIgnoringLocalCacheData`). We own success caching (file cache, above)
  and frames are immutable, so HTTP caching would only risk negatively-caching a
  404 for a not-yet-generated frame and serving that stale 404 to retries.
